          Introduction

           

          When we do an elam on N9K (Tahoe platform) for multidestination traffic , we often see met_ptr as outgoing interface info. Lets try to identify what that met_ptr is pointing to with specfic topology. Before checking met_ptr , please try to pick the topology that is a somewhat match to your specific scenario.

           

          Overall process here is (hoping it will help us without getting confused, specially when we are on call with customer) ; We are taking elam on ingress port i.e specific asic/slice. Then we are pulling information from two tables tah_<asic_name>_qsmt_met and tah_<asic_name>_qsmt_ovtbl.

           

          First table is using pointer value (met0_idx) that we get from elam ; to find ovidx value in order to find appropriate port on specific asic/slice. But based on my observations, first check will not provide us all ports on specific asic/slice so You will need to keep on using next_ptr value from qsmt_met table (until it is no longer present) to find all ports in ingress ports asic/slice.

           

          Now what if port is different asic/slice, then start using same process for asic/slice using met0_idx pointer from Elam, untill you find your port in Question

           

           

          Topology-1  Non-VXLAN L3 multicast topology

           

          Topology shown below is typical network set up with two pair of vPC peers (Tahoe dav/bigsky) and RP(T2). Multicast receiver 10.10.10.100 is has reqeusted traffic for group 239.1.1.1. Src is 20.20.20.100.  software image is 9.3(1)

          !! !! 0x300 === 0011 0000 0000
          !! above data pattern is in HEX; if we convert into bits and count from right to left starting with zero. 
          We see 8 and 9 bits           are set. Next we need to check asic0/slic2 for Sport=8 and 9. 
          
module-1(TAH-elam-insel6)# 
module-1(TAH-elam-insel6)# !! 8 and 9 th bit is set, which means peer-link ports
